inues to fight in Afghanistan, and the military may soon have a heightened presence elsewhere in the Middle East and in Africa. As such, Rules of Disengagement provides inspiration and lessons for anyone who opposes an interventionist US military policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAfghan War, 2001-xMoral and ethical aspects. 0aIraq War, 2003-2011xMoral and ethical aspects. 0aMilitary ethicszUnited States. 0aSelective conscientious objectionzUnited States. 0aSoldiersxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xMoral and ethical aspects. 0aWarxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aGilberd, Kathleen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814762929.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814762929zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814762929/original  a978-3-11-070644-4 New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA